article.headline: Bowen gets open for late 3-pointer to lead Spartans

images.name: Shimek_Liz 010603 Inline
images.caption: Michigan State's Liz Shimek enjoys the horn sounding on the Spartans' 67-62 upset of Purdue.

article.linkText: Two freshmen lead Michigan State to upset of No. 6 Purdue
article.story:
EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Lindsay Bowen and Liz Shimek looked
like anything but freshmen while leading Michigan State to an upset
victory over Purdue (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today; No. 7 Associated Press).

<photo1>

	   Bowen was especially effective in the closing moments, nailing a
3-pointer with 24.5 seconds left and two free throws after that to
seal a 67-62 victory Monday night.

	   Michigan State improved to 7-5 overall, 1-1 in the Big Ten.
Purdue fell to 11-2, 0-1.

	   ''Coach has been telling me to have confidence and I had an open
look and it fell,'' Bowen said about the decisive 3-pointer. ''We
feel like we can beat anybody.''

	   Purdue coach Kristy Curry was not pleased with her team's
late-game defense.

	   ''She was wide open,'' Curry said of Bowen. ''Anybody in the
country that has watched summer basketball knows she can shoot.''

	   Although Purdue was playing its third game in six days, Curry
didn't use fatigue as a crutch.

	   ''There are no excuses,'' she said. ''Obviously, we thought we
were mature enough for the situation. I knew coming in it would be
tough.''

	   Bowen's 21 points paced the Spartans and Shimek added 19 points and
nine rebounds while playing all 40 minutes.

	   Shereka Wright led the Boilermakers with 18 points and 12
rebounds.

	   Michigan State outscored Purdue 37-30 in the second half and
outrebounded the Boilermakers 35-33 in the game.

	   ''I can't even explain this feeling, it's so great,'' Shimek
said after going 9-for-12 from the field.

	   Purdue took a 32-30 lead into halftime on Mary Jo Noon's layup
just before the break. It was the Boilermakers' first lead since
2-0.

	   Noon finished with 12 points and eight rebounds. Erika Valek
also scored 12 for Purdue.

	   In the second half, Purdue took a 46-40 lead with 15:32
remaining. But consecutive baskets by Shimek brought the Spartans
back for good. Shimek also was a step ahead of the 6-foot-5 Noon
all game.

	   ''When you put your mind to something and you go for that ball,
you're going to get it,'' Shimek said. ''We worked hard and it came
out our way.''

	   For Michigan State, the upset victory comes at a perfect time after
the Spartans dropped a disappointing 52-46 decision to Northwestern
-- a team that hadn't won a Big Ten regular-season game in 43 tries.

	   ''There was a lot of anger from the Northwestern game,''
Spartans coach Joanne P. McCallie said. ''There was definitely a
carryover effect there.''

	   With her 6-for-6 night at the free throw line, Bowen now has made
the first 32 free-throw attempts of her career.
